      <item>
        <title>PSI as expected</title>
        <dc:creator><![CDATA[luisherranz]]></dc:creator>
        <description><![CDATA[
            <p>Hey guys, it looks like the main performance problem was simply embedding the fonts in the HTML. Google doesn’t like it. Once I removed it, scores went up to 95.</p>
<p>I have been using the Gatsby version of the TwentyTwenty theme as comparison, to make sure we are in the same performance ranges:</p>
<ul>
<li>Gatsby (max 97, consistent 95): <a href="https://gatsby-starter-wordpress-twenty-twenty.netlify.app/">https://gatsby-starter-wordpress-twenty-twenty.netlify.app/</a>
</li>
<li>Frontity, no fonts (max 98, consistent 95): <a href="https://twentytwenty-theme-example-fv50lfzyq.now.sh">https://twentytwenty-theme-example-fv50lfzyq.now.sh</a>
</li>
</ul>
<p><em>I removed the featured images from the Frontity version to do a fair comparison with the Gatsby version, which doesn’t have featured images.</em></p>
<p><strong>This is totally my fault</strong> as I was the one suggesting to use the embedding technique in the first place. I’ve done a PR to fix it: <a href="https://github.com/frontity/frontity/pull/406">https://github.com/frontity/frontity/pull/406</a></p>
          <p><a href="https://community.frontity.org/t/psi-as-expected/1617/16">Read full topic</a></p>
        ]]></description>
        <link>https://community.frontity.org/t/psi-as-expected/1617/16</link>
        <pubDate>Tue, 28 Apr 2020 14:54:26 +0000</pubDate>
        <guid isPermaLink="false">community.frontity.org-post-1617-16</guid>
